# Future Problems Resulting from Scarce Resources: An In-Depth Analysis

Resource scarcity is an escalating global challenge with profound implications for economic development, social stability, and environmental sustainability. As the world population grows and consumption patterns intensify, the pressure on finite natural resources intensifies, leading to a cascade of complex problems. This report provides a comprehensive analysis of the future problems that will result from scarce resources, drawing on recent, reliable sources and data to present an objective and detailed overview.

## 1. Introduction

Scarcity of natural resources refers to the situation where the consumption of resources exceeds their natural replenishment rates. This phenomenon affects both renewable resources (such as water, forests, and arable land) and non-renewable resources (such as fossil fuels and minerals). The consequences of resource scarcity are multifaceted, impacting food security, water availability, energy supply, economic growth, social cohesion, and geopolitical stability.

## 2. Drivers of Resource Scarcity

### Population Growth and Rising Demand

The global population is projected to increase from approximately 8 billion in 2025 to over 9 billion by 2050, with significant growth in urban and middle-class populations, particularly in developing countries like China and India. This demographic shift is expected to drive a surge in demand for food, water, energy, and raw materials.

- Food demand is projected to increase by 70% by 2050 to feed the expanding population ([BBC News, 2012](https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-16391040)).
- Water demand is expected to rise by 32-40% by 2050, primarily driven by manufacturing, electricity generation, and agriculture ([Roland Berger, 2018](https://www.rolandberger.com/en/Insights/Publications/Trend-Compendium-2030-Megatrend-3.html); [PwC, 2023](https://www.pwc.co.uk/issues/megatrends/climate-change-and-resource-scarcity.html)).

### Climate Change

Climate change acts as a "threat multiplier" by exacerbating resource vulnerabilities. Changes in temperature, precipitation patterns, and the frequency of extreme weather events reduce agricultural productivity, diminish water availability, and degrade ecosystems essential for resource renewal.

- Agricultural productivity in parts of Africa could decline by up to one-third over the next 60 years due to climate change ([PwC, 2023](https://www.pwc.co.uk/issues/megatrends/climate-change-and-resource-scarcity.html)).
- Melting glaciers, droughts, and desertification contribute to water shortages and loss of arable land, particularly in vulnerable regions such as Latin America, Africa, and the Middle East ([The Open Web Project, 2023](https://theowp.org/crisis_index/climate-and-environmental-conflicts/)).

### Unsustainable Consumption and Economic Growth Models

Current economic growth models, especially in developing countries, often prioritize rapid development over environmental sustainability, leading to overexploitation of natural resources.

- Developing countries frequently exploit lands and forests unsustainably to meet economic goals, accelerating resource depletion ([Springer, 2019](https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-22974-0_107)).
- The demand for critical raw materials, such as rare earth elements and metals, is increasing, with supply concentrated in specific regions, creating geopolitical risks ([Roland Berger, 2018](https://www.rolandberger.com/en/Insights/Publications/Trend-Compendium-2030-Megatrend-3.html)).

## 3. Projected Future Problems from Resource Scarcity

### 3.1 Food Insecurity and Agricultural Challenges

The need to produce 70% more food by 2050 to feed the growing population will be challenged by limited arable land, water scarcity, and climate-induced productivity declines.

- Urbanization is displacing millions of hectares of fertile agricultural land annually, equivalent to the size of Italy in less than 20 years ([BBC News, 2012](https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-16391040)).
- Droughts and soil degradation reduce crop yields and increase the risk of famine and malnutrition, especially in vulnerable regions ([UIA Encyclopedia, 2022](http://encyclopedia.uia.org/en/problem/133899)).

### 3.2 Water Scarcity and Stress

Water scarcity is already widespread and expected to worsen, with over 50% of the global population living in water-stressed areas by 2050.

| Aspect                  | Projection/Fact                                   | Source                                         |
|-------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| Increase in water demand | 32-40% by 2050                                  | Roland Berger (2018); PwC (2023)               |
| Population in water-stressed areas | Over 50% by 2050                        | Roland Berger (2018)                            |
| Causes                  | Drought, pollution, over-irrigation, conflict   | BBC News (2012); The Open Web Project (2023)  |

Water scarcity leads to reduced agricultural output, health risks, and increased competition for water resources, often sparking social unrest and conflict.

### 3.3 Energy Crisis and Resource Depletion

Non-renewable energy resources such as oil, coal, and natural gas are depleting rapidly, with oil reserves projected to last about 30 more years at current consumption rates.

- The cost of extracting oil and minerals is increasing as reserves become harder to access, doubling the cost of average oil wells in the past decade ([BBC News, 2012](https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-16391040)).
- Energy demand is projected to rise by 50% by 2030, intensifying pressure on finite fossil fuel resources ([PwC, 2023](https://www.pwc.co.uk/issues/megatrends/climate-change-and-resource-scarcity.html)).

### 3.4 Environmental Degradation and Biodiversity Loss

Overexploitation of resources leads to deforestation, soil erosion, loss of biodiversity, and pollution, which undermine ecosystem services essential for human survival.

- The loss of forests and natural habitats accelerates species extinction and reduces the planet's capacity to renew resources ([UIA Encyclopedia, 2022](http://encyclopedia.uia.org/en/problem/133899)).
- Pollution and resource depletion transform free goods like air and water into economic goods requiring costly purification ([PEPED, 2021](https://peped.org/economicinvestigations/2634/)).

### 3.5 Social Unrest, Conflict, and Geopolitical Tensions

Resource scarcity is a significant driver of social instability and conflict, particularly in regions with weak governance and high ethnic or political fragmentation.

- At least 40% of intrastate conflicts over the past 60 years have links to natural resources ([IISD, 2009](https://www.iisd.org/publications/conflict-peacebuilding-role-natural-resources-and-environment)).
- Water disputes, such as those involving the Nile River basin, have escalated tensions and military threats ([The Open Web Project, 2023](https://theowp.org/crisis_index/climate-and-environmental-conflicts/)).
- Climate change-induced resource shortages contributed to the 2010 Arab Spring through drought-induced migration and food price spikes ([The Open Web Project, 2023](https://theowp.org/crisis_index/climate-and-environmental-conflicts/)).

### 3.6 Economic Impacts and Declining Productivity

Resource depletion threatens economic growth by increasing costs, reducing productivity, and causing social and environmental costs.

- Unsustainable consumption patterns lead to irreversible climate change and economic decline due to increased social, economic, and environmental costs ([Springer, 2019](https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-22974-0_107)).
- Developing countries reliant on resource exports face economic vulnerabilities as resources become scarce or depleted ([Springer, 2019](https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-22974-0_107)).

## 4. Interconnectedness of Problems and Feedback Loops

Resource scarcity problems are interconnected, often creating vicious cycles:

| Cycle Component               | Description                                                                                  |
|------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Resource degradation → Conflict | Depletion of resources leads to competition and conflict, which further degrades resources.  |
| Climate change → Resource scarcity | Climate change reduces resource availability, intensifying scarcity and related conflicts.   |
| Urbanization → Loss of arable land | Expanding cities consume fertile land, reducing food production capacity.                    |
| Economic growth → Resource overexploitation | Pursuit of growth accelerates resource depletion, undermining long-term sustainability.     |

These feedback loops exacerbate the severity and complexity of future problems.

## 5. Potential Mitigation and Policy Approaches

While the challenges are formidable, there are pathways to mitigate future problems:

- **Sustainable Resource Management:** Implementing policies for rational use and conservation of renewable resources to maintain their renewal capacity ([UIA Encyclopedia, 2022](http://encyclopedia.uia.org/en/problem/133899)).
- **Technological Innovation:** Developing efficient technologies for resource extraction, renewable energy, and sustainable agriculture ([Conard, 2015](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/277377340_Some_Challenges_to_Sustainability)).
- **International Cooperation:** Managing transboundary resources through cooperative frameworks to reduce conflict risks ([IISD, 2009](https://www.iisd.org/publications/conflict-peacebuilding-role-natural-resources-and-environment)).
- **Climate Change Mitigation:** Reducing greenhouse gas emissions to limit climate impacts on resource availability ([PwC, 2023](https://www.pwc.co.uk/issues/megatrends/climate-change-and-resource-scarcity.html)).
- **Population and Consumption Control:** Promoting family planning and sustainable consumption patterns to reduce demand pressures ([Course Hero, 2023](https://www.coursehero.com/file/pdav50/What-future-problems-would-result-from-scarce-resources-The-biggest-problem-with/)).

## 6. Conclusion

The future problems resulting from scarce resources are multifaceted and deeply interconnected, encompassing food and water insecurity, energy crises, environmental degradation, social unrest, and economic instability. These challenges are driven primarily by population growth, climate change, and unsustainable consumption patterns. Without significant changes in resource management, economic models, and international cooperation, the world faces escalating conflicts, humanitarian crises, and irreversible environmental damage.

Addressing these issues requires a systemic approach that integrates environmental sustainability with social and economic development goals. Policymakers, scientists, and global institutions must collaborate to implement innovative solutions and equitable resource governance to avert the looming crises associated with resource scarcity.

